  <h1>Beneficiary Letter — United States</h1>
  <p><strong>Prepared for:</strong> [Borrower Name] | <strong>Date:</strong> [Date]</p>

  <h2>What is an EPM?</h2>
  <p>The Equity Preservation Mortgage (EPM) is a non-traditional mortgage secured by your home. Loan proceeds are invested; investment returns are used to pay mortgage interest and provide you monthly income. Your home remains yours.</p>

  <h2>What Your Beneficiaries Inherit</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The Property:</strong> Your home, subject to the outstanding mortgage</li>
    <li><strong>Estate Value:</strong> Property proceeds MINUS mortgage balance</li>
    <li><strong>NNEG Protection:</strong> No Negative Equity Guarantee ensures they cannot inherit debt exceeding property value</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Settlement Steps</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Lender is notified of your passing</li>
    <li>Estate representative contacts Lender</li>
    <li>Mortgage balance is determined</li>
    <li>Options: (a) Sell property, pay Lender from proceeds, remainder to estate; OR (b) Refinance/assume loan</li>
    <li>If property value < loan balance, NNEG insurance pays the difference. No deficiency judgment against estate.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Important Notes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Step-Up in Basis:</strong> When you pass, your beneficiaries receive a "step-up" in tax basis. This typically results in little or no capital gains tax if they sell shortly after.</li>
    <li><strong>No Deficit:</strong> NNEG insurance ensures your estate is never liable for debt exceeding property value.</li>
    <li><strong>Estate Tax:</strong> Your estate may be subject to Federal estate tax if total estate exceeds $13.61M (2024 exemption). Consult a tax advisor on minimization strategies.</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Beneficiaries should seek independent legal and tax counsel regarding estate settlement and any IRS obligations.</strong></p>
</div>

